WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:04.930 --> 00:00:05.860
Stanford University.

00:00:10.230 --> 00:00:12.084
Let us get started here.

00:00:16.170 --> 00:00:19.680
So picking up from the other
day, where have we gotten?

00:00:19.680 --> 00:00:21.020
Not very far.

00:00:21.020 --> 00:00:23.860
Behavior-- full
range variability

00:00:23.860 --> 00:00:26.450
of sexual behaviors,
fixed action patterns.

00:00:26.450 --> 00:00:27.730
Is this kind of dark here?

00:00:27.730 --> 00:00:30.350
No.

00:00:30.350 --> 00:00:32.460
Seeing in some ways
what's interesting

00:00:32.460 --> 00:00:36.910
is the conservative nature of
sexual behavior across species,

00:00:36.910 --> 00:00:39.130
other ways the sheer
variety, trying

00:00:39.130 --> 00:00:42.850
to make sense of what aspects
of human behavior are unique,

00:00:42.850 --> 00:00:43.630
all of that.

00:00:43.630 --> 00:00:46.300
Then beginning to march
backwards-- what goes on

00:00:46.300 --> 00:00:50.780
in the nervous system one second
before sexual behavior occurs?

00:00:50.780 --> 00:00:53.850
And marching through the
relevant limbic structures,

00:00:53.850 --> 00:00:56.900
some of which have
strong sex differences,

00:00:56.900 --> 00:00:58.520
some of which don't.

00:00:58.520 --> 00:01:02.590
Seeing some ways in
which neurotransmitters

00:01:02.590 --> 00:01:05.980
in the whole world of dopamine
complicates things enormously,

00:01:05.980 --> 00:01:07.820
marching through there.

00:01:07.820 --> 00:01:11.220
Where we had then gotten
to was asking, OK, so

00:01:11.220 --> 00:01:14.270
what sort of bits of information
in the environment, what

00:01:14.270 --> 00:01:17.570
sort of ethological
releasing stimuli

00:01:17.570 --> 00:01:20.210
can trigger the nervous
system to do its thing?

00:01:20.210 --> 00:01:21.860
And you've got the drill by now.

00:01:21.860 --> 00:01:23.540
So what we had done
was look at a couple

00:01:23.540 --> 00:01:25.890
of different sensory
systems, and we had just

00:01:25.890 --> 00:01:28.900
started to wallow in
the world of pheromones,

00:01:28.900 --> 00:01:30.900
of pheromonal communication.

00:01:30.900 --> 00:01:35.630
What we ended with was number
one, the hormone dependency

00:01:35.630 --> 00:01:40.440
of generating sexually
meaningful pheromones,

00:01:40.440 --> 00:01:42.860
that business being
that males have to have

00:01:42.860 --> 00:01:44.110
sufficient testosterone.

00:01:44.110 --> 00:01:46.430
Females have to have
ovaries on board

00:01:46.430 --> 00:01:50.190
to be producing pheromones
that carry sexual meaning.

00:01:50.190 --> 00:01:52.110
What is the reason for that?

00:01:52.110 --> 00:01:54.950
The fact that a whole lot
of the actual chemicals that

00:01:54.950 --> 00:01:58.540
constitute sexually meaningful
pheromones are made out

00:01:58.540 --> 00:02:01.280
of some sex hormone
breakdown products

00:02:01.280 --> 00:02:04.900
and the sheer bizarrity but
eventual wonderful clarity

00:02:04.900 --> 00:02:08.340
of what's up with perfumes.

00:02:08.340 --> 00:02:10.509
Then transitioning
at the very end

00:02:10.509 --> 00:02:13.640
to the business about how your
endocrine status has a lot

00:02:13.640 --> 00:02:17.820
to do with your perception of
pheromones from the other sex,

00:02:17.820 --> 00:02:20.840
that women who are
ovariectomized to low estrogen

00:02:20.840 --> 00:02:24.330
levels have trouble being
able to differentiate

00:02:24.330 --> 00:02:27.780
the smell of males and
females, men and women.

00:02:27.780 --> 00:02:30.230
And estrogen replacement
takes care of that.

00:02:30.230 --> 00:02:34.150
The exact same thing when you
take away testosterone for men,

00:02:34.150 --> 00:02:37.810
and what we were just about to
get to before we had to stop

00:02:37.810 --> 00:02:40.180
was one additional
thing, which is

00:02:40.180 --> 00:02:42.610
one's opinion about
the pheromones

00:02:42.610 --> 00:02:44.130
that you were smelling.

00:02:44.130 --> 00:02:45.830
And this goes back
to a literature,

00:02:45.830 --> 00:02:48.180
a really interesting
one showing that

00:02:48.180 --> 00:02:51.440
not only are women
better at differentiating

00:02:51.440 --> 00:02:54.260
between the smell
of men and women--

00:02:54.260 --> 00:02:56.790
gonadally intact men and women.

00:02:56.790 --> 00:02:58.310
Not only are they
better at doing

00:02:58.310 --> 00:03:00.460
that around the
point of ovulation,

00:03:00.460 --> 00:03:03.950
but their preference
for the smell of males

00:03:03.950 --> 00:03:08.020
gets more dramatic around
the time of ovulation.

00:03:08.020 --> 00:03:10.490
Meanwhile, over at the
male end of things,

00:03:10.490 --> 00:03:14.340
something rather
similar in terms of what

00:03:14.340 --> 00:03:15.610
you make of the pheromones.

00:03:15.610 --> 00:03:21.210
And this was a famous classic
study in which women volunteers

00:03:21.210 --> 00:03:23.840
had their armpits swabbed
at different points

00:03:23.840 --> 00:03:27.730
in their menstrual cycle and
put into little sealed jars,

00:03:27.730 --> 00:03:30.530
and all sorts of male
volunteers sniffing them

00:03:30.530 --> 00:03:32.880
and rating their pleasantness.

00:03:32.880 --> 00:03:36.420
And what you found
was on the average,

00:03:36.420 --> 00:03:40.220
the odorants were rated in
the unpleasant direction,

00:03:40.220 --> 00:03:43.270
but they were rated as least
unpleasant around the time

00:03:43.270 --> 00:03:44.750
that women are ovulating.

00:03:44.750 --> 00:03:47.960
And I think once we get
past the world of armpit

00:03:47.960 --> 00:03:51.060
smells in little
glass jars, one can

00:03:51.060 --> 00:03:55.460
get into the more ethologically
relevant world of men prefer

00:03:55.460 --> 00:03:57.840
pheromones derived from
women around the time

00:03:57.840 --> 00:03:59.290
when women are ovulating.

00:03:59.290 --> 00:04:01.450
Once again, a
testosterone-dependent

00:04:01.450 --> 00:04:03.030
phenomenon.

00:04:03.030 --> 00:04:05.520
What we now begin
to look at are some

00:04:05.520 --> 00:04:10.560
of the physiological effects of
sexual pheromones between sexes

00:04:10.560 --> 00:04:11.740
within sexes.

00:04:11.740 --> 00:04:14.790
One example you heard about
in the very first lecture,

00:04:14.790 --> 00:04:17.730
which is that whole business,
that Wellesley effect

00:04:17.730 --> 00:04:20.680
the ability of females of all
sorts of different species,

00:04:20.680 --> 00:04:23.180
including college
freshman human females,

00:04:23.180 --> 00:04:25.980
to synchronize each
other's cycles,

00:04:25.980 --> 00:04:29.770
this being done with pheromones,
intersexual perception

00:04:29.770 --> 00:04:32.040
of pheromones, so
the Wellesley effect.

00:04:32.040 --> 00:04:35.220
What's also shown in a
number of rodent species

00:04:35.220 --> 00:04:39.020
is the pheromones, the
smell of an adult female,

00:04:39.020 --> 00:04:44.380
will delay the onset of
puberty of younger females.

00:04:44.380 --> 00:04:46.220
And how might one frame that?

00:04:46.220 --> 00:04:49.960
That is utterly a gene
competition sort of strategy

00:04:49.960 --> 00:04:50.510
there.

00:04:50.510 --> 00:04:52.740
This is reproductive
competition.

00:04:52.740 --> 00:04:56.890
If you arrest the development
of the other females around you,

00:04:56.890 --> 00:05:00.290
you are going to leave
more copies, et cetera.

00:05:00.290 --> 00:05:03.290
Meanwhile, a
literature of intramale

00:05:03.290 --> 00:05:05.730
physiological
effects-- what happens

00:05:05.730 --> 00:05:08.360
to the physiology of
males in various species

00:05:08.360 --> 00:05:11.340
when smelling the
pheromones of other males?

00:05:11.340 --> 00:05:13.670
What you see, first
off, is it depends

00:05:13.670 --> 00:05:17.470
on who the other guy you're
smelling, the dominance rank.

00:05:17.470 --> 00:05:21.050
In lots of rodent species and
some primate species as well,

00:05:21.050 --> 00:05:23.860
males are able to
differentiate between smells

00:05:23.860 --> 00:05:26.416
of very high ranking males
and very low ranking ones,

00:05:26.416 --> 00:05:27.290
and what do you know?

00:05:27.290 --> 00:05:29.750
They're not all that upset
about the low ranking ones.

00:05:29.750 --> 00:05:33.020
What do you see in terms of
the physiological effects

00:05:33.020 --> 00:05:34.900
in the number of
species when males

00:05:34.900 --> 00:05:38.610
are smelling the pheromones
of big, healthy, strapping,

00:05:38.610 --> 00:05:40.420
androgenic other males?

00:05:40.420 --> 00:05:44.310
In some cases, it drives down
their testosterone levels.

00:05:44.310 --> 00:05:47.660
They're totally
physiologically intimidated,

00:05:47.660 --> 00:05:50.440
this being some great
competitive strategy

00:05:50.440 --> 00:05:52.650
for males who could pump
out just the right kind

00:05:52.650 --> 00:05:54.300
of suppressive pheromones.

00:05:54.300 --> 00:05:56.430
In other species,
though, what you

00:05:56.430 --> 00:05:59.610
see is a sudden burst
of sperm production,

00:05:59.610 --> 00:06:01.140
and what's that about?

00:06:01.140 --> 00:06:03.410
Another version of
the same logic-- this

00:06:03.410 --> 00:06:05.240
is a counter-strategy.

00:06:05.240 --> 00:06:09.160
If males have come up, evolved
the means in various rodent

00:06:09.160 --> 00:06:13.390
species to generate pheromones
that will drive down

00:06:13.390 --> 00:06:16.370
testosterone levels in
opponents, what males also

00:06:16.370 --> 00:06:19.770
want to have evolve with some
mechanism of when smelling

00:06:19.770 --> 00:06:22.370
those sorts of pheromones
to try to counter that

00:06:22.370 --> 00:06:25.740
by increasing sperm production.

00:06:25.740 --> 00:06:30.030
What we have here is a
co-evolutionary arms race.

00:06:30.030 --> 00:06:34.549
Terms of interactions of
pheromones between the sexes,

00:06:34.549 --> 00:06:36.340
and what I've been
doing here is describing

00:06:36.340 --> 00:06:38.530
all this without
making use of this,

00:06:38.530 --> 00:06:40.910
so what you see
is physiologically

00:06:40.910 --> 00:06:43.740
when the female is
the pheromone donor,

00:06:43.740 --> 00:06:46.580
and the other recipient is
a female in terms of, say,

00:06:46.580 --> 00:06:49.960
puberty, decreasing
puberty onset,

00:06:49.960 --> 00:06:53.420
and what we just saw with
male is donor versus male

00:06:53.420 --> 00:06:56.830
is in some ways suppressing
some endpoint's testosterone,

00:06:56.830 --> 00:06:59.820
in some ways increasing
sperm production.

00:06:59.820 --> 00:07:02.220
What you see in lots
of rodent species,

00:07:02.220 --> 00:07:05.990
when you're looking at
between genders, when males

00:07:05.990 --> 00:07:08.660
are the source of
pheromones among rodents,

00:07:08.660 --> 00:07:14.030
it accelerates puberty
onset in the females.

00:07:14.030 --> 00:07:17.360
And when you've got
females as the donors,

00:07:17.360 --> 00:07:21.090
it increases testosterone
level and sperm production

00:07:21.090 --> 00:07:23.550
in the males of lots
of different species.

00:07:23.550 --> 00:07:26.160
So all this makes
wonderful, wonderful, sort

00:07:26.160 --> 00:07:29.560
of sociobiological sense in
terms of how this should work.

00:07:29.560 --> 00:07:31.910
Elaborations on this, of course.

00:07:31.910 --> 00:07:35.240
What you also see is
not only puberty onset

00:07:35.240 --> 00:07:36.580
and being regulated.

00:07:36.580 --> 00:07:38.970
You also see in all
sorts of species

00:07:38.970 --> 00:07:43.780
where you can induce
ovulation by sensory stimuli.

00:07:43.780 --> 00:07:47.770
What you see is the
smell of a female

00:07:47.770 --> 00:07:52.030
will decrease the likelihood
of induced ovulation.

00:07:52.030 --> 00:07:55.200
Female-- the smell of
a male will increase

00:07:55.200 --> 00:07:56.490
the likelihood of ovulation.

00:07:56.490 --> 00:07:58.890
All sorts of species
that do not have

00:07:58.890 --> 00:08:02.250
automatic rhythms of
ovulation cycles of that way,

00:08:02.250 --> 00:08:04.060
but rather they are induced.

00:08:04.060 --> 00:08:07.510
And one classic example
of that are pigs.

00:08:07.510 --> 00:08:10.760
Pigs are inducible ovulators,
if you've always wondered

00:08:10.760 --> 00:08:12.330
whether that's the case or not.

00:08:12.330 --> 00:08:15.820
And you can go and
recreationally buy

00:08:15.820 --> 00:08:18.140
a variant of pig pheromone.

00:08:18.140 --> 00:08:20.900
This is known as Boar
Mate, and no doubt,

00:08:20.900 --> 00:08:23.076
that's not only patent
pended, but somewhere out

00:08:23.076 --> 00:08:24.450
in the Midwest,
there's all sorts

00:08:24.450 --> 00:08:27.010
of TV jingles about Boar Mate.

00:08:27.010 --> 00:08:34.370
And Boar Mate is an ovulation
inducer in female boars

00:08:34.370 --> 00:08:37.929
and involving a same
male-derived pheromone,

00:08:37.929 --> 00:08:41.350
which are found in truffles,
truffles which somehow

00:08:41.350 --> 00:08:45.480
have stumbled on the means to
induce female pigs to ovulate.

00:08:45.480 --> 00:08:49.060
And no doubt, that's explaining
some very interesting

00:08:49.060 --> 00:08:53.330
interspecies interactions,
so that being another realm.

00:08:53.330 --> 00:08:56.020
Inducible all
physiological changes--

00:08:56.020 --> 00:08:59.160
in this case, one classic
demonstration of it.

00:08:59.160 --> 00:09:02.650
In this case,
probably pheromones

00:09:02.650 --> 00:09:06.690
of female causing an indirect
measure of testosterone levels

00:09:06.690 --> 00:09:07.540
in a male.

00:09:07.540 --> 00:09:10.030
This is a classic
paper, and you will

00:09:10.030 --> 00:09:12.600
note that I didn't
say females and males.

00:09:12.600 --> 00:09:14.660
Saying a female and a male.

00:09:14.660 --> 00:09:18.370
This was a classic paper in
nature some 30 years ago or so,

00:09:18.370 --> 00:09:22.030
which was written by the very
famous and well-known doctor

00:09:22.030 --> 00:09:23.200
Anonymous.

00:09:23.200 --> 00:09:26.040
The author's name was
not published there.

00:09:26.040 --> 00:09:30.050
And this was a researcher
who did research

00:09:30.050 --> 00:09:33.830
in an unspecified hemisphere
with an unspecified species,

00:09:33.830 --> 00:09:37.410
but involved long stretches of
being at a research facility

00:09:37.410 --> 00:09:40.480
completely on his own in
isolation from other humans,

00:09:40.480 --> 00:09:42.820
and all sorts of people in
the business for decades

00:09:42.820 --> 00:09:45.310
afterward have been speculating
on who the author is.

00:09:45.310 --> 00:09:47.660
And it's generally understood.

00:09:47.660 --> 00:09:50.610
And what this person noted
was every now and then,

00:09:50.610 --> 00:09:53.550
he would pick up and
go to the city that

00:09:53.550 --> 00:09:56.970
was a three-hour
seaplane flight away

00:09:56.970 --> 00:09:59.200
or some such thing,
where among other things,

00:09:59.200 --> 00:10:03.040
he had a highly significant
other with a great deal

00:10:03.040 --> 00:10:06.336
of physical intimacy
and all that stuff

00:10:06.336 --> 00:10:08.400
from kind of the right
side of the chart.

00:10:08.400 --> 00:10:11.110
And what he noticed
was what he perceived

00:10:11.110 --> 00:10:13.650
to be an extraordinary
difference in what he

00:10:13.650 --> 00:10:18.940
was subjectively interpreting
as testosterone-driven mood

00:10:18.940 --> 00:10:22.550
and level of energy and all of
that depending on where he was.

00:10:22.550 --> 00:10:24.930
Not quite being the
type of field ethologist

00:10:24.930 --> 00:10:27.350
that took blood from
himself, what he did instead

00:10:27.350 --> 00:10:30.590
was take an indirect assay
building on the well-known fact

00:10:30.590 --> 00:10:32.140
that testosterone
has something to do

00:10:32.140 --> 00:10:34.760
with the rate of beard growth.

00:10:34.760 --> 00:10:37.610
And what he wound up
doing was very soon,

00:10:37.610 --> 00:10:40.680
having a razor there
every day, shaving,

00:10:40.680 --> 00:10:43.990
and getting the little bits
of stubble, and weighing it.

00:10:43.990 --> 00:10:47.000
Weighing it is an indirect
assay of testosterone levels,

00:10:47.000 --> 00:10:50.330
and what was shown was
sit out there by himself

00:10:50.330 --> 00:10:52.365
with whatever ungulates
he was obsessing over,

00:10:52.365 --> 00:10:53.990
and this sort of rate
of beard growth--

00:10:53.990 --> 00:10:57.270
go back to the rest of the
world, and it does this.

00:10:57.270 --> 00:10:59.760
And this square wave
going on like that,

00:10:59.760 --> 00:11:03.810
this as a very-- and OK, what
are all the confounds here?

00:11:03.810 --> 00:11:05.620
It's not clear if
it was pheromones.

00:11:05.620 --> 00:11:07.490
Maybe it was actually
being in proximity

00:11:07.490 --> 00:11:09.770
to the newspaper
in the town that he

00:11:09.770 --> 00:11:11.240
returned to now and then.

00:11:11.240 --> 00:11:12.950
Maybe there was a
confound of whatever

00:11:12.950 --> 00:11:15.690
aftershave he was using
that was doing something

00:11:15.690 --> 00:11:16.700
rather to his testes.

00:11:16.700 --> 00:11:18.660
Nonetheless,
generally interpreted

00:11:18.660 --> 00:11:21.510
as this being a really
interesting, indirect,

00:11:21.510 --> 00:11:24.920
and equal-- was one
example of induction

00:11:24.920 --> 00:11:27.880
of physiological
changes in human males

00:11:27.880 --> 00:11:30.600
by pheromones from females.

00:11:30.600 --> 00:11:33.450
So if you ever meet Dr.
Anonymous, who interestingly,

00:11:33.450 --> 00:11:35.850
has been publishing
papers for about 300 years

00:11:35.850 --> 00:11:39.310
or so every now and then,
congratulate that individual

00:11:39.310 --> 00:11:41.280
on the research.

00:11:41.280 --> 00:11:44.600
So pheromonal stuff--
now elaborations of it,

00:11:44.600 --> 00:11:47.230
which you should be able
to derive all on your own

00:11:47.230 --> 00:11:49.710
from some of our
principles by now, which

00:11:49.710 --> 00:11:54.780
is, what if for example,
you are a female donor

00:11:54.780 --> 00:11:57.200
and female recipient,
and the whole logic

00:11:57.200 --> 00:12:00.720
here being decrease the
likelihood of ovulation?

00:12:00.720 --> 00:12:02.620
Delay the onset of puberty.

00:12:02.620 --> 00:12:06.490
What if these are siblings,
if these are two sisters?

00:12:06.490 --> 00:12:08.670
And you were off and
running with that one.

00:12:08.670 --> 00:12:10.830
It will not work as effectively.

00:12:10.830 --> 00:12:12.940
Easy kin selection argument.

00:12:12.940 --> 00:12:15.450
So all sorts of
aspects of relatedness,

00:12:15.450 --> 00:12:18.160
you will not have your
testosterone levels driven up

00:12:18.160 --> 00:12:21.520
if you are a hamster, and you
were smelling your sister,

00:12:21.520 --> 00:12:25.870
all that sort of thing that
makes perfect sense by now.

00:12:25.870 --> 00:12:30.350
Now switching over-- one last
piece of business, though.

00:12:30.350 --> 00:12:33.590
In terms of the pheromonal
attractiveness stuff,

00:12:33.590 --> 00:12:38.150
a handful of studies showing
that among homosexual men, what

00:12:38.150 --> 00:12:42.770
you have is it's the smell of
men who are preferred to women,

00:12:42.770 --> 00:12:45.020
and it's when men have
higher testosterone

00:12:45.020 --> 00:12:48.500
levels that they are preferred.

00:12:48.500 --> 00:12:52.670
And what we've got there
is an exact same physiology

00:12:52.670 --> 00:12:56.300
in a somewhat going in the
opposite direction, flipping

00:12:56.300 --> 00:13:00.230
of things that sure argues for
some interesting biological

00:13:00.230 --> 00:13:01.220
underpinnings.

00:13:01.220 --> 00:13:07.800
One final thing-- women not only
prefer the smell of men when

00:13:07.800 --> 00:13:09.880
around the time that
they are ovulating.

00:13:09.880 --> 00:13:13.420
Their noses selectively
become more sensitive to such

00:13:13.420 --> 00:13:17.560
smells, and estrogen has
all sorts of receptors

00:13:17.560 --> 00:13:19.900
on olfactory neurons.

00:13:19.900 --> 00:13:21.680
So that makes sense.

00:13:21.680 --> 00:13:24.370
Leaping over to other
sensory systems--

00:13:24.370 --> 00:13:26.650
