That means around
the time that women

00:27:04.010 --> 00:27:06.610
are ovulating,
thanks to estrogen,

00:27:06.610 --> 00:27:08.830
they are more
sensitive to touch.

00:27:08.830 --> 00:27:12.380
And I'm sure this has been
studied in consenting hamsters,

00:27:12.380 --> 00:27:15.050
but my bet is that more
sensitive to tactile

00:27:15.050 --> 00:27:18.240
stimulation in some parts
of the body over others.

00:27:18.240 --> 00:27:21.990
What estrogen also is
doing, as we just heard,

00:27:21.990 --> 00:27:23.715
is working on the
olfactory system

00:27:23.715 --> 00:27:27.800
and lowering thresholds for
detecting the smell of males.

00:27:27.800 --> 00:27:30.940
So we've got all sorts
of ways within the brain

00:27:30.940 --> 00:27:34.890
and in the periphery to
bias towards more arousal

00:27:34.890 --> 00:27:35.680
at that time.

00:27:35.680 --> 00:27:38.050
Wonderful evolutionary biology.

00:27:38.050 --> 00:27:39.630
No problem at all.

00:27:39.630 --> 00:27:42.110
One additional piece
of the female story,

00:27:42.110 --> 00:27:45.370
which is the effects over the
course of this kind of time

00:27:45.370 --> 00:27:48.890
span-- weeks to months to
years or so-- the effects

00:27:48.890 --> 00:27:52.180
of those androgens,
those male sex hormones

00:27:52.180 --> 00:27:53.960
that females are releasing.

00:27:53.960 --> 00:27:55.720
And what you see
there is that plays

00:27:55.720 --> 00:27:59.700
a role in proceptivity,
increasing sexual arousal,

00:27:59.700 --> 00:28:02.070
sexual motivation.

00:28:02.070 --> 00:28:05.610
Meanwhile, on the other side
of the road, we've got males,

00:28:05.610 --> 00:28:08.960
and what does testosterone--
testosterone over

00:28:08.960 --> 00:28:11.280
this time span-- what
does it have to do

00:28:11.280 --> 00:28:13.830
with sexual behavior in males?

00:28:13.830 --> 00:28:16.860
Well, on first pass,
it sure looks like it

00:28:16.860 --> 00:28:19.170
has a lot to do with it.

00:28:19.170 --> 00:28:20.970
What sort of evidence?

00:28:20.970 --> 00:28:23.890
Initially, correlative evidence.

00:28:23.890 --> 00:28:28.410
Well, the time of year
in various species

00:28:28.410 --> 00:28:31.320
where males do their
mating is the time of year

00:28:31.320 --> 00:28:34.140
when testosterone
levels are elevated.

00:28:34.140 --> 00:28:36.790
Over the life span,
testosterone levels

00:28:36.790 --> 00:28:39.530
go up around puberty
and from about age

00:28:39.530 --> 00:28:44.040
30 on, very gently cascade
down into alarming senescence,

00:28:44.040 --> 00:28:47.170
and what you see there is
a similar profile in terms

00:28:47.170 --> 00:28:48.660
of sexual behavior.

00:28:48.660 --> 00:28:50.410
That does not tell us much.

00:28:50.410 --> 00:28:51.970
These are correlations.

00:28:51.970 --> 00:28:55.250
Furthermore, correlative
studies in humans, a handful,

00:28:55.250 --> 00:28:58.240
showing more sexually
active men tend

00:28:58.240 --> 00:29:00.400
to have higher
testosterone levels,

00:29:00.400 --> 00:29:02.500
and for what it's worth,
a number of studies

00:29:02.500 --> 00:29:05.980
have documented a dramatic
drop in testosterone levels

00:29:05.980 --> 00:29:10.390
in men right around the time
that they become fathers.

00:29:10.390 --> 00:29:10.890
OK.

00:29:10.890 --> 00:29:12.110
So figure that one out.

00:29:12.110 --> 00:29:15.470
Also an increase in vasopressin
levels at that time.

00:29:15.470 --> 00:29:18.660
You know how to interpret
this one by now.

00:29:18.660 --> 00:29:21.880
So we've got testosterone
and higher levels

00:29:21.880 --> 00:29:25.040
of male sexual behavior
going hand in hand.

00:29:25.040 --> 00:29:28.000
Are we looking at
any causality here?

00:29:28.000 --> 00:29:30.870
First off, we already know
about one piece of causality,

00:29:30.870 --> 00:29:35.980
which was the other day, sexual
behavior in men, in males,

00:29:35.980 --> 00:29:38.110
increases testosterone levels.

00:29:38.110 --> 00:29:41.080
So that's one reason why
they may go hand in hand.

00:29:41.080 --> 00:29:42.790
In that scenario,
testosterone has

00:29:42.790 --> 00:29:47.270
nothing to do with increasing
the likelihood of the behavior.

00:29:47.270 --> 00:29:49.320
So does testosterone
actually have

00:29:49.320 --> 00:29:52.700
a causal role in
increasing the likelihood

00:29:52.700 --> 00:29:54.660
of male sexual behavior?

00:29:54.660 --> 00:29:57.050
And the answer is yes.

00:29:57.050 --> 00:29:58.210
And how do you show it?

00:29:58.210 --> 00:30:00.950
With the most simple classic
way of doing something

00:30:00.950 --> 00:30:03.780
in an endocrine study,
which is get rid

00:30:03.780 --> 00:30:05.710
of the guy's testosterone.

00:30:05.710 --> 00:30:08.730
And you castrate the
male, your rodent male,

00:30:08.730 --> 00:30:10.780
your non-human
primate male, and what

00:30:10.780 --> 00:30:16.080
you see is there is a big drop
in levels of sexual behavior.

00:30:16.080 --> 00:30:20.640
And this could range from male
lever pressing to get access

00:30:20.640 --> 00:30:23.560
to a female to
courtship displays

00:30:23.560 --> 00:30:27.170
to extent of pomading
of hair or something

00:30:27.170 --> 00:30:30.180
in the right neighborhoods,
and whatever the measure is,

00:30:30.180 --> 00:30:33.390
this is when normal testosterone
levels are on board.

00:30:33.390 --> 00:30:39.030
And this is after castration,
a very, very dramatic drop.

00:30:39.030 --> 00:30:43.200
Now to fulfill the second
ironclad requirement

00:30:43.200 --> 00:30:46.050
in endocrinology, the last
thing you need to do now

00:30:46.050 --> 00:30:50.340
is after the
subtraction experiment,

00:30:50.340 --> 00:30:52.310
to do a replacement one.

00:30:52.310 --> 00:30:55.180
Artificially give
back the normal levels

00:30:55.180 --> 00:30:58.430
to the castrated individual,
and levels of sexual behavior

00:30:58.430 --> 00:30:59.800
go back to there.

00:30:59.800 --> 00:31:00.521
Whoa.

00:31:00.521 --> 00:31:01.020
OK.

00:31:01.020 --> 00:31:05.180
That proves that we have a
causal relationship here.

00:31:05.180 --> 00:31:06.970
Not so fast.

00:31:06.970 --> 00:31:11.830
First thing to note, which
is 0% testosterone and sexual

00:31:11.830 --> 00:31:13.860
behavior goes way, way down.

00:31:13.860 --> 00:31:15.610
It doesn't go to zero.

00:31:15.610 --> 00:31:18.190
In every species
looked at, starting

00:31:18.190 --> 00:31:21.420
with the embarrassing sexual
behavior of everyone's pet dogs

00:31:21.420 --> 00:31:24.750
when they were six years old,
even after being neutered, what

00:31:24.750 --> 00:31:28.680
you see is there's a level
of residual sexual behavior--

00:31:28.680 --> 00:31:32.230
rodents, dogs, primates,
including humans.

00:31:32.230 --> 00:31:34.140
This is a critical point.

00:31:34.140 --> 00:31:37.480
How much residual
sexual behavior

00:31:37.480 --> 00:31:39.630
is there after castration?

00:31:39.630 --> 00:31:43.740
The more sexual experience
before castration,

00:31:43.740 --> 00:31:47.650
the more there is going
to be retained afterward.

00:31:47.650 --> 00:31:52.380
In other words, on a certain
like totally artificial level,

00:31:52.380 --> 00:31:54.170
this amount of
sexual behavior is

00:31:54.170 --> 00:31:56.150
being driven by testosterone.

00:31:56.150 --> 00:31:58.650
This amount, which
persists here,

00:31:58.650 --> 00:32:00.910
is being driven by
social experience.

00:32:00.910 --> 00:32:03.480
It's got nothing to
do with the hormones.

00:32:03.480 --> 00:32:05.520
Yes, this is ridiculous
dichotomizing

00:32:05.520 --> 00:32:08.500
into this, but the fact
that it doesn't go to zero,

00:32:08.500 --> 00:32:10.700
and the fact that the
more sexual experience

00:32:10.700 --> 00:32:14.240
pre-castration, the more
residual behavior, this

00:32:14.240 --> 00:32:16.740
is a vote for just
how much of a role

00:32:16.740 --> 00:32:21.210
social experience, social
conditioning plays.

00:32:21.210 --> 00:32:23.650
Next thing that takes
away from the yes,

00:32:23.650 --> 00:32:25.630
it's all caused
by testosterone--

00:32:25.630 --> 00:32:28.270
now you do an
elaboration on the study.

00:32:28.270 --> 00:32:31.870
You castrate a male,
and now instead

00:32:31.870 --> 00:32:35.040
of replacing with
100% of normal levels,

00:32:35.040 --> 00:32:38.870
you give 10% of
normal levels, or you

00:32:38.870 --> 00:32:41.580
give 200% of normal levels.

00:32:41.580 --> 00:32:43.060
And what do you wind up seeing?

00:32:43.060 --> 00:32:47.070
If testosterone plays a
strictly causative role, even

00:32:47.070 --> 00:32:50.040
in this range, you are
going to get something--

00:32:50.040 --> 00:32:52.050
this is going to
be lower than 100%,

00:32:52.050 --> 00:32:53.530
and this is going to be higher.

00:32:53.530 --> 00:32:56.310
That's not what you see.

00:32:56.310 --> 00:32:59.310
Instead, it is
something like that.

00:32:59.310 --> 00:33:01.770
You get roughly the
same reinstatement

00:33:01.770 --> 00:33:07.300
of sexual behavior when you
return testosterone levels

00:33:07.300 --> 00:33:09.890
over anything
roughly approximating

00:33:09.890 --> 00:33:12.490
the normal physiological range.

00:33:12.490 --> 00:33:14.340
What does that tell you?

00:33:14.340 --> 00:33:18.080
The brain circuits we learned
about the other day involved

00:33:18.080 --> 00:33:22.000
in sexual motivation-- it
requires testosterone around

00:33:22.000 --> 00:33:25.610
to work fully, not
entirely, but to work fully.

00:33:25.610 --> 00:33:29.300
But those brain
regions are not really

00:33:29.300 --> 00:33:33.290
all that concerned with the
exact level of testosterone.

00:33:33.290 --> 00:33:37.640
Rough approximation of normal,
rough approximation of normal

00:33:37.640 --> 00:33:39.600
has the exact same effect.

00:33:39.600 --> 00:33:42.220
If you were seeing
a tight relationship

00:33:42.220 --> 00:33:45.920
in a male between the
amount of sexual behavior

00:33:45.920 --> 00:33:48.030
and testosterone
levels, it's not

00:33:48.030 --> 00:33:51.540
because every little smidgen
bit of more testosterone

00:33:51.540 --> 00:33:54.270
is going to drive
more sexual behavior.

00:33:54.270 --> 00:33:57.490
It's because every little
additional smidgen of behavior

00:33:57.490 --> 00:34:00.500
is going to drive higher
testosterone levels.

00:34:00.500 --> 00:34:03.240
So we've got this really
important observation.

00:34:03.240 --> 00:34:07.110
Yes, testosterone is needed
in species after species,

00:34:07.110 --> 00:34:11.290
including humans, for the
normal range of sexual behavior.

00:34:11.290 --> 00:34:15.699
Just as importantly, castration
never drops it down to zero.

00:34:15.699 --> 00:34:18.570
The more social experience,
that whole song and dance,

00:34:18.570 --> 00:34:21.880
and very importantly
as well, the system

00:34:21.880 --> 00:34:24.960
is not sensitive to
little differences

00:34:24.960 --> 00:34:26.580
in testosterone levels.

00:34:26.580 --> 00:34:29.530
Stating that a different
way, if some guy has

00:34:29.530 --> 00:34:32.330
one and 1/2 percent
more testosterone

00:34:32.330 --> 00:34:34.860
on board than the guy
sitting next to him

00:34:34.860 --> 00:34:37.940
or than he had last week,
is that going to mean he

00:34:37.940 --> 00:34:41.270
is going to be more sexually
motivated, more aroused?

00:34:41.270 --> 00:34:42.670
No, not at all.

00:34:42.670 --> 00:34:46.620
Within the normal range, the
system doesn't distinguish it.

00:34:46.620 --> 00:34:49.870
The relevant brain regions
are sensitive to testosterone

00:34:49.870 --> 00:34:54.090
and require it, but do not care
a whole lot about the levels.

00:34:54.090 --> 00:34:57.240
One exception, which is
if you instead of, say,

00:34:57.240 --> 00:35:02.210
200%, push testosterone
levels like 1000%,

00:35:02.210 --> 00:35:07.270
tenfold higher than normal,
this is supraphysiological,

00:35:07.270 --> 00:35:09.670
which means it's out of
the normal range, which

00:35:09.670 --> 00:35:12.810
means no bodies normally
generate those sorts of levels.

00:35:12.810 --> 00:35:15.910
Put it up in that range,
and you will get an increase

00:35:15.910 --> 00:35:18.820
in sexual behavior
and sexual arousal.

00:35:18.820 --> 00:35:20.650
When do you see this?

00:35:20.650 --> 00:35:24.300
The idiots who go and
abuse anabolic steroids

00:35:24.300 --> 00:35:27.400
for their weight lifting or
whatever, people doing that

00:35:27.400 --> 00:35:29.920
are not pushing up their
testosterone levels

00:35:29.920 --> 00:35:34.140
into the higher range of what
human bodies can generate.

00:35:34.140 --> 00:35:37.280
They are pushing it way
above the normal range.

00:35:37.280 --> 00:35:40.850
In that range, you
do see an increase

00:35:40.850 --> 00:35:43.600
in sexual proceptivity.

00:35:43.600 --> 00:35:48.450
In a week or so, what we will
see is the exact same story.

00:35:48.450 --> 00:35:51.170
It will be the exact
same chart here when

00:35:51.170 --> 00:35:53.330
asking the question,
what does testosterone

00:35:53.330 --> 00:35:55.030
have to do with aggression?

00:35:55.030 --> 00:35:58.230
And what you'll see is the
exact same conclusions.

00:35:58.230 --> 00:36:00.400
What are we beginning
to see here?

00:36:00.400 --> 00:36:05.040
That testosterone is not playing
a strictly causative role.

00:36:05.040 --> 00:36:07.140
It is playing one
of the words that

00:36:07.140 --> 00:36:10.420
should be becoming repetitive
here and clearly really

00:36:10.420 --> 00:36:11.140
important.

00:36:11.140 --> 00:36:15.120
Testosterone is playing
a modulatory role.

00:36:15.120 --> 00:36:18.730
What testosterone
does is sensitize you

00:36:18.730 --> 00:36:24.320
towards stimuli that are
evocative of sexual arousal.

00:36:24.320 --> 00:36:27.340
It lowers the
threshold, and that

00:36:27.340 --> 00:36:29.410
could be shown in
all sorts of studies,

00:36:29.410 --> 00:36:33.670
but where it's most clear
cut is in this case.

00:36:33.670 --> 00:36:36.730
Does testosterone cause
this sexual behavior?

00:36:36.730 --> 00:36:40.690
No, but when it is on
board, it facilitates it.

00:36:40.690 --> 00:36:42.270
It modulates it.

00:36:42.270 --> 00:36:44.570
Theme again and again and again.

00:36:44.570 --> 00:36:48.400
And that, obviously, has tons to
do with individual differences.

00:36:48.400 --> 00:36:52.720
One last hormone to mention in
this realm of hormone levels

00:36:52.720 --> 00:36:55.000
over the last couple of
weeks, months, seasons,

00:36:55.000 --> 00:36:57.420
or so-- the hormone melatonin.

00:36:57.420 --> 00:36:59.640
And I think that's the
only time melatonin is

00:36:59.640 --> 00:37:01.090
going to be mentioned in class.

00:37:01.090 --> 00:37:04.800
Melatonin has something to do
with telling the body what time

00:37:04.800 --> 00:37:06.036
of year it is.

00:37:06.036 --> 00:37:10.400
It is responsive to the amount
of light you are exposed to.

00:37:10.400 --> 00:37:12.140
What is melatonin about?

00:37:12.140 --> 00:37:15.510
It is one of the driving
forces on seasonal mating.

00:37:15.510 --> 00:37:19.500
Those species where you
suddenly get on one afternoon

00:37:19.500 --> 00:37:22.650
each year, all the wildebeests
ovulate the same afternoon

00:37:22.650 --> 00:37:25.030
kind of thing-- it
is almost certainly

00:37:25.030 --> 00:37:28.700
a whole pathway in the brain
sensitive to the amount

00:37:28.700 --> 00:37:32.440
of light and the amount of
light per day over recent weeks,

00:37:32.440 --> 00:37:34.640
which by way of
melatonin, triggers

00:37:34.640 --> 00:37:36.850
the onset of the mating season.

00:37:36.850 --> 00:37:39.320
Do humans have a
seasonal mating pattern?

00:37:39.320 --> 00:37:42.420
There's a smidgen
of evidence for it.

00:37:42.420 --> 00:37:45.760
If we've got it, it is
a very, very weak echo

00:37:45.760 --> 00:37:49.800
of what you see in
some other species.

00:37:49.800 --> 00:37:53.350
Now we shift over to getting
really way back then.

00:37:53.350 --> 00:37:55.530
Instead of over
your last 28 days

00:37:55.530 --> 00:37:58.290
or over the last three
seasons, now beginning to

00:37:58.290 --> 00:38:01.160
look at perinatal factors.

00:38:01.160 --> 00:38:03.330
Perinatal-- before birth.

00:38:03.330 --> 00:38:05.120
Prenatal-- after birth.

00:38:05.120 --> 00:38:08.030
Postnatal-- very
early development.

00:38:08.030 --> 00:38:11.720
First off, focusing
on early environment,

00:38:11.720 --> 00:38:14.030
environmental factors
having something

00:38:14.030 --> 00:38:16.030
to do with adult
sexual behavior.

00:38:16.030 --> 00:38:18.480
What we can translate
that into is

00:38:18.480 --> 00:38:21.440
ways in which early environment
affects every single one

00:38:21.440 --> 00:38:22.940
of these subsequent ones.

00:38:22.940 --> 00:38:25.080
What does early
environment childhood

00:38:25.080 --> 00:38:28.250
have to do with shaping
of sexual behavior?

00:38:28.250 --> 00:38:32.210
A theme that's also going
to come out in every topic

00:38:32.210 --> 00:38:35.040
we're going to hear of
after this, buzz words that

00:38:35.040 --> 00:38:37.750
should be beginning to be
keeping you awake at night--

00:38:37.750 --> 00:38:41.870
modulatory, contingent,
if then, all that stuff.

00:38:41.870 --> 00:38:43.320
Here is another one.

00:38:43.320 --> 00:38:45.940
Here's another concept
that comes through.

00:38:45.940 --> 00:38:50.870
The evidence shows that there
is very little about early life

00:38:50.870 --> 00:38:55.010
experience, which
influences the quality,

00:38:55.010 --> 00:38:59.400
the way in which an organism
goes about having sex.

00:38:59.400 --> 00:39:01.110
What's another
way of stating it?

00:39:01.110 --> 00:39:04.950
This is a pretty set in stone
bunch of fixed action patterns.

00:39:04.950 --> 00:39:09.720
Early experience is not about
learning how to be sexual.

00:39:09.720 --> 00:39:11.920
Early experience
is about learning

00:39:11.920 --> 00:39:15.810
the appropriate social
contexts for being so.

00:39:15.810 --> 00:39:19.040
And that is shown in
species after species.

00:39:19.040 --> 00:39:21.310
That is what
experience is about.

00:39:21.310 --> 00:39:23.970
Not how to do it,
but when to do it

00:39:23.970 --> 00:39:26.140
and who you should
not in your right mind

00:39:26.140 --> 00:39:29.750
try to do something proceptive
to and things of that sort.

00:39:29.750 --> 00:39:32.069
This is what early
experience is about.

00:39:32.069 --> 00:39:33.610
And what we're going
to see in a week

00:39:33.610 --> 00:39:36.860
is the exact same
boring paragraph.

00:39:36.860 --> 00:39:40.770
Early experience does not teach
organisms how to be aggressive.

00:39:40.770 --> 00:39:43.780
It teaches organisms
the appropriate context

00:39:43.780 --> 00:39:45.910
for being aggressive.

00:39:45.910 --> 00:39:48.930
So what's the sort of evidence
for these early effects?

00:39:48.930 --> 00:39:51.210
One example, the
whole literature

00:39:51.210 --> 00:39:53.790
that emerged that is covered
somewhat in the zebra

00:39:53.790 --> 00:39:57.080
book in another domain, but this
whole literature that emerged

00:39:57.080 --> 00:40:01.500
in the 1950s, work looking
at captive primates, what

00:40:01.500 --> 00:40:04.130
are the consequences
of growing up

00:40:04.130 --> 00:40:06.830
in a certain degree
of social isolation?

00:40:06.830 --> 00:40:09.940
What happens to behavior--
and eventually, people

00:40:09.940 --> 00:40:12.070
studying behavior
and physiology-- what

00:40:12.070 --> 00:40:16.740
happens to behavior in adulthood
if you are a young rhesus

00:40:16.740 --> 00:40:20.880
monkey, who grows up only
with peers and no mother,

00:40:20.880 --> 00:40:23.940
or grows up only with
a mother and no peers,

00:40:23.940 --> 00:40:26.110
or grows up with
Mother being present

00:40:26.110 --> 00:40:29.860
only intermittently, or at
the most extremes, growing up

00:40:29.860 --> 00:40:32.500
with neither mother nor
peers or any other member

00:40:32.500 --> 00:40:33.939
of your species around?

00:40:33.939 --> 00:40:35.730
You will see in the
