was another one of those front
page stories in Time, Newsweek,

01:07:43.110 --> 01:07:45.070
et cetera, and this
came a couple of years

01:07:45.070 --> 01:07:49.410
after Simon Levey's finding of
that sexually dimorphic nucleus

01:07:49.410 --> 01:07:51.100
in the brain, that
whole deal there.

01:07:51.100 --> 01:07:55.060
And this was the reporting
of the first genetic markers

01:07:55.060 --> 01:07:57.450
for sexual orientation.

01:07:57.450 --> 01:07:59.680
And this was reported
by a geneticist

01:07:59.680 --> 01:08:01.310
at National Institute
of Health, a guy

01:08:01.310 --> 01:08:05.610
named Dean Hamer, who was a
very well-respected geneticist.

01:08:05.610 --> 01:08:11.020
And what he reported was that
he was finding genetic markers

01:08:11.020 --> 01:08:13.410
for sexual orientation.

01:08:13.410 --> 01:08:16.660
In other words, certain
gene locations that

01:08:16.660 --> 01:08:21.069
were more likely to be shared
between gay siblings, where

01:08:21.069 --> 01:08:25.189
both were gay, than
between partially

01:08:25.189 --> 01:08:29.193
gay siblings or non-gay siblings
or however that one runs.

01:08:29.193 --> 01:08:30.720
You know that one by now.

01:08:30.720 --> 01:08:33.334
Beginning to find genetic
markers going with this.

01:08:33.334 --> 01:08:37.149
This was really interesting,
and no surprise--

01:08:37.149 --> 01:08:39.630
what the newspapers were
screaming about within days

01:08:39.630 --> 01:08:41.210
was scientists
announced today they

01:08:41.210 --> 01:08:45.870
have discovered the gay gene.

01:08:45.870 --> 01:08:46.600
Great.

01:08:46.600 --> 01:08:50.040
Maybe we shouldn't let people
learn any science out there.

01:08:50.040 --> 01:08:53.520
So scientists have
discovered the gay gene.

01:08:53.520 --> 01:08:55.840
It goes to all the newspapers
and Reader's Digest,

01:08:55.840 --> 01:08:58.609
and if I recall at the
time, Ronald Reagan as well,

01:08:58.609 --> 01:09:01.099
but he was completely
demented at that point,

01:09:01.099 --> 01:09:02.390
so I won't hold it against him.

01:09:02.390 --> 01:09:04.660
But the people at Newsweek
should have known better.

01:09:04.660 --> 01:09:08.180
So we have cover stories
about the gay gene.

01:09:08.180 --> 01:09:10.880
Obviously, you can rip
this to shreds right now.

01:09:10.880 --> 01:09:13.160
Number one, this was not a gene.

01:09:13.160 --> 01:09:14.770
This was a genetic marker.

01:09:14.770 --> 01:09:18.319
You remember the other
week, the difference there.

01:09:18.319 --> 01:09:23.490
Number two, there was
no consistency in this.

01:09:23.490 --> 01:09:25.085
What do I mean by this?

01:09:25.085 --> 01:09:28.649
This pair of
identical twins would

01:09:28.649 --> 01:09:32.859
tend to share a certain genetic
marker, which was predictive

01:09:32.859 --> 01:09:34.560
of sexual orientation.

01:09:34.560 --> 01:09:39.609
And the next pair over, it
wasn't the same area of genes

01:09:39.609 --> 01:09:41.370
that showed that covariance.

01:09:41.370 --> 01:09:43.149
It would be a completely
different area

01:09:43.149 --> 01:09:44.439
that they had in common.

01:09:44.439 --> 01:09:47.020
In another pair, a
completely different area,

01:09:47.020 --> 01:09:52.189
you got this genetic covariance
in various twin pairs,

01:09:52.189 --> 01:09:55.500
but it wasn't the same gene
marker in all those cases.

01:09:55.500 --> 01:09:57.260
All of them were
different, which

01:09:57.260 --> 01:10:00.250
makes zero sense in
terms of the genetics.

01:10:00.250 --> 01:10:03.370
The biggest problem with it
is that since then, all sorts

01:10:03.370 --> 01:10:05.320
of people have tried to
replicate the finding,

01:10:05.320 --> 01:10:07.110
and it has never
been replicated.

01:10:07.110 --> 01:10:10.610
Nonetheless, Hamer became
quite famous for this.

01:10:10.610 --> 01:10:13.340
He is gay, and he used this
sort of politically some

01:10:13.340 --> 01:10:16.550
of the same ways that Simon
Levey did with his study, which

01:10:16.550 --> 01:10:18.370
is, don't tell me about choice.

01:10:18.370 --> 01:10:21.220
Don't tell me about my
neurotic mother anymore.

01:10:21.220 --> 01:10:25.300
We are looking at a very hard
wired biological trait-- what

01:10:25.300 --> 01:10:27.050
sexual orientation you have.

01:10:27.050 --> 01:10:29.450
Levey's finding I have
found quite convincing

01:10:29.450 --> 01:10:31.010
in terms of replications.

01:10:31.010 --> 01:10:34.910
Hamer's-- nobody else has
replicated any actual genetics

01:10:34.910 --> 01:10:36.010
that he reported.

01:10:36.010 --> 01:10:37.910
Makes no sense at all.

01:10:37.910 --> 01:10:41.730
So great limitations in
what you could make of this.

01:10:41.730 --> 01:10:42.390
OK.

01:10:42.390 --> 01:10:46.040
This allows us to make our
great final leap to the left

01:10:46.040 --> 01:10:47.640
with this thing,
this logic that's

01:10:47.640 --> 01:10:49.950
going to run through
everything we talk about,

01:10:49.950 --> 01:10:52.850
which is the second you're
talking about genes,

01:10:52.850 --> 01:10:57.600
you are implicitly talking
about the evolutionary history

01:10:57.600 --> 01:10:59.910
that brought about the
existence of those genes.

01:10:59.910 --> 01:11:03.480
And that you're also talking
about the proteins made

01:11:03.480 --> 01:11:06.750
by those genes and early
environment changing

01:11:06.750 --> 01:11:10.430
the epigenetic state of
transcribing those genes.

01:11:10.430 --> 01:11:12.320
Yes, yes, that whole
song and dance now.

01:11:12.320 --> 01:11:16.960
So now we have to transition to,
what does evolutionary biology

01:11:16.960 --> 01:11:19.330
tell us about sexual behavior?

01:11:19.330 --> 01:11:22.290
So the first thing that it tells
us is absolutely obvious, which

01:11:22.290 --> 01:11:26.520
is organisms have sex for
the good of the species.

01:11:26.520 --> 01:11:27.900
So that one's out of the way.

01:11:27.900 --> 01:11:31.630
So now we go to what is
much more logically in terms

01:11:31.630 --> 01:11:34.180
of contemporary, evolutionary
thinking-- contemporary

01:11:34.180 --> 01:11:37.450
starting circa 1965 or
so-- the whole notion

01:11:37.450 --> 01:11:40.200
of maximizing the number of
copies of your own genes,

01:11:40.200 --> 01:11:44.230
all of that translated into
sort of the economic terms

01:11:44.230 --> 01:11:45.950
of [INAUDIBLE] copies of genes.

01:11:45.950 --> 01:11:49.090
What that basically
states is sexual behavior

01:11:49.090 --> 01:11:51.660
is about reproduction.

01:11:51.660 --> 01:11:54.640
And people who would
study phenomena

01:11:54.640 --> 01:11:57.050
like these in various
rodent species

01:11:57.050 --> 01:12:00.400
or wildebeest ovulating the
same afternoon, all of that,

01:12:00.400 --> 01:12:04.850
would say, yes, indeed, you
only have sexual behavior

01:12:04.850 --> 01:12:10.230
when it's around the time when
females are ovulating and yes.

01:12:10.230 --> 01:12:12.800
Reproductive behavior
is about reproduction.

01:12:12.800 --> 01:12:14.970
It's about passing
on copies of genes.

01:12:14.970 --> 01:12:19.200
What soon began to fall apart
was not only making sense of us

01:12:19.200 --> 01:12:23.360
with our having non-reproductive
sex all sorts of times,

01:12:23.360 --> 01:12:25.980
was the discovery that we're
not the only species that

01:12:25.980 --> 01:12:26.760
does that.

01:12:26.760 --> 01:12:30.010
And far and away
the flagship species

01:12:30.010 --> 01:12:34.700
as a sort of emblem of
that are bonobo chimps,

01:12:34.700 --> 01:12:38.130
who are, according to almost
all primatologists out there,

01:12:38.130 --> 01:12:40.413
the coolest primate
species there is.

01:12:40.413 --> 01:12:40.913
OK.

01:12:40.913 --> 01:12:42.620
Bonobo chimps-- they
were historically

01:12:42.620 --> 01:12:46.850
known as pygmy chimps, which is
to say that when people first

01:12:46.850 --> 01:12:49.220
discovered them in
terms of scientists,

01:12:49.220 --> 01:12:51.200
they were viewed as,
well, these are chimps,

01:12:51.200 --> 01:12:54.284
but they're just kind of
weirdo atrophied chimps, which

01:12:54.284 --> 01:12:55.700
I don't quite know
how you come up

01:12:55.700 --> 01:12:58.170
with a pygmy atrophied
chimp, but that was the view.

01:12:58.170 --> 01:13:00.680
And not very interesting--
what eventually became clear

01:13:00.680 --> 01:13:03.780
is they are a separate
species of chimp,

01:13:03.780 --> 01:13:06.610
and bonobo chimps
are utterly different

01:13:06.610 --> 01:13:10.510
from your standard issue
Jane Goodall chimps.

01:13:10.510 --> 01:13:14.010
Again, Jane Goodall chimps,
we have a tournament species

01:13:14.010 --> 01:13:17.140
with extreme high levels
of male aggression.

01:13:17.140 --> 01:13:19.260
As we will hear
about next week, you

01:13:19.260 --> 01:13:21.620
have chimps who are
building weapons.

01:13:21.620 --> 01:13:23.630
You have chimps
that form something

01:13:23.630 --> 01:13:26.880
resembling organized
warfare, and meanwhile,

01:13:26.880 --> 01:13:29.840
over, as it turned out, on
the other side of the Congo,

01:13:29.840 --> 01:13:31.930
which is where the
main division occurs,

01:13:31.930 --> 01:13:35.490
you only find bonobos in
one area of the Congo basin,

01:13:35.490 --> 01:13:38.220
and they clearly have been
reproductively isolated

01:13:38.220 --> 01:13:40.400
from all the rest of
the chimps heading there

01:13:40.400 --> 01:13:43.850
east all the way to the Indian
Ocean by way of the Congo.

01:13:43.850 --> 01:13:45.830
There, go on the other
side of the river.

01:13:45.830 --> 01:13:50.530
You've got the bonobos, and
bonobos are totally different.

01:13:50.530 --> 01:13:56.170
Bonobos, unlike chimps, have
virtually no sexual dimorphism,

01:13:56.170 --> 01:13:58.250
so you're off and
running with that one.

01:13:58.250 --> 01:14:00.380
We know exactly what that means.

01:14:00.380 --> 01:14:05.970
Bonobo chimps have female
dominance rather than male.

01:14:05.970 --> 01:14:09.558
All bonobo chimps play the
guitar and sing soulfully.

01:14:12.480 --> 01:14:13.560
What else?

01:14:13.560 --> 01:14:16.740
And we have astonishing
amounts of sex.

01:14:16.740 --> 01:14:17.600
Wait a second.

01:14:17.600 --> 01:14:19.380
We just went off the rails here.

01:14:19.380 --> 01:14:21.960
A species with low degrees
of aggression, because they

01:14:21.960 --> 01:14:24.080
have virtually no aggression
whatsoever, species

01:14:24.080 --> 01:14:27.970
with low degree of aggression
and with no sexual dimorphism

01:14:27.970 --> 01:14:29.760
in body size-- what
we're looking at

01:14:29.760 --> 01:14:32.790
is a pair bonding species,
a monogamous species.

01:14:32.790 --> 01:14:36.110
Bonobos are not a
monogamous species.

01:14:36.110 --> 01:14:40.590
Bonobos make-- I don't know
who-- look like a pair bonding

01:14:40.590 --> 01:14:41.820
species by comparison.

01:14:41.820 --> 01:14:46.050
Bonobos are the most sexually
promiscuous species on Earth.

01:14:46.050 --> 01:14:49.300
Bonobos have astonishing
amounts of sex

01:14:49.300 --> 01:14:52.390
with every other type of
bonobo they could run into.

01:14:52.390 --> 01:14:54.750
They have sex in
order to reproduce.

01:14:54.750 --> 01:14:57.360
They have sex in order
to decrease tensions.

01:14:57.360 --> 01:14:59.010
They have sex in
order to celebrate

01:14:59.010 --> 01:15:00.610
having decreased tensions.

01:15:00.610 --> 01:15:03.290
They have sex, because it's an
even numbered day of the month,

01:15:03.290 --> 01:15:04.420
because this is odd.

01:15:04.420 --> 01:15:07.250
Every variety, and
the vast majority

01:15:07.250 --> 01:15:10.490
of it being non-reproductive,
non-reproductive

01:15:10.490 --> 01:15:14.280
because it's not at a time
when anybody's ovulating,

01:15:14.280 --> 01:15:16.400
or because it's with
someone of the same sex,

01:15:16.400 --> 01:15:19.190
or it involves sexual behavior,
which traditionally does not

01:15:19.190 --> 01:15:21.760
result in eggs getting
fertilized and all sorts

01:15:21.760 --> 01:15:24.162
of variants that
people only dream about

01:15:24.162 --> 01:15:25.620
from buying books
and trying to get

01:15:25.620 --> 01:15:27.120
lessons and this sort of thing.

01:15:27.120 --> 01:15:29.320
And you have, perhaps,
having something

01:15:29.320 --> 01:15:32.520
to do with that astonishingly
limber spinal columns,

01:15:32.520 --> 01:15:34.830
but what you've got is a
totally different picture.

01:15:34.830 --> 01:15:35.760
Wait a second.

01:15:35.760 --> 01:15:38.540
They are very low
aggression, and they

01:15:38.540 --> 01:15:41.110
have no sexual dimorphism,
but they're as far

01:15:41.110 --> 01:15:43.010
from pair bonding
as you can get.

01:15:43.010 --> 01:15:46.080
And instead, you have a highly
promiscuous social system,

01:15:46.080 --> 01:15:47.810
female-dominated,
and they're all

01:15:47.810 --> 01:15:50.490
just so cool and wonderful
you can't believe it.

01:15:50.490 --> 01:15:53.120
And every time people go
to primatology meetings,

01:15:53.120 --> 01:15:56.740
if you study some dumb old
stupid species like a baboon,

01:15:56.740 --> 01:15:58.580
you spend the whole
time basically feeling

01:15:58.580 --> 01:16:00.320
like you're some sort
of immature jerk,

01:16:00.320 --> 01:16:02.390
because you're not
hanging out with bonobos.

01:16:02.390 --> 01:16:05.460
They are the kings of
primatologists these days,

01:16:05.460 --> 01:16:06.830
the people who study bonobos.

01:16:06.830 --> 01:16:10.600
As the soundbite goes,
chimpanzees are from Mars.

01:16:10.600 --> 01:16:13.540
Bonobos are from Venus.

01:16:13.540 --> 01:16:14.110
OK.

01:16:14.110 --> 01:16:17.040
So that's what the t-shirts
say from the bonobo people

01:16:17.040 --> 01:16:18.460
at the conferences there.

01:16:18.460 --> 01:16:19.810
Totally different system.

01:16:19.810 --> 01:16:22.960
So what we already see is
violating our simple rules

01:16:22.960 --> 01:16:25.220
of what predicts a
tournament species

01:16:25.220 --> 01:16:26.850
and what predicts
a pair bonding one.

01:16:26.850 --> 01:16:29.979
What's most striking
here is [INAUDIBLE]

01:16:29.979 --> 01:16:31.520
reproductive behavior
is reproduction

01:16:31.520 --> 01:16:32.970
for passing on
copies of the genes,

01:16:32.970 --> 01:16:34.020
not for the good of the species.

01:16:34.020 --> 01:16:36.145
But we know individual
selection could [INAUDIBLE].

01:16:36.145 --> 01:16:39.430
And here's these guys having
sex with 14 other bonobos

01:16:39.430 --> 01:16:42.140
while they're all upside
down or who knows what,

01:16:42.140 --> 01:16:46.700
and it's not just for passing
on numbers of copies of genes.

01:16:46.700 --> 01:16:49.240
Huge, huge exception there.

01:16:49.240 --> 01:16:52.050
And huge exception in
lots of other species.

01:16:52.050 --> 01:16:54.180
And the ecologist
Joan Roughgarden

01:16:54.180 --> 01:16:56.110
here in the biology
department has

01:16:56.110 --> 01:16:59.860
made an argument there is far
more non-reproductive sex that

01:16:59.860 --> 01:17:01.770
goes on in lots of
different species,

01:17:01.770 --> 01:17:05.470
weakening the classic
Darwinian concept from three,

01:17:05.470 --> 01:17:07.870
four weeks ago of
sexual selection

01:17:07.870 --> 01:17:10.380
being a very important
driving force.

01:17:10.380 --> 01:17:12.992
What sex is very heavily
about is one gender choosing

01:17:12.992 --> 01:17:14.700
who are going to mate
with the other one,

01:17:14.700 --> 01:17:17.200
and it's all driven by
that of seeing instead

01:17:17.200 --> 01:17:19.390
if the world of
bonobos, there's not

01:17:19.390 --> 01:17:23.670
a whole lot of evolutionary
drive being built around sex

01:17:23.670 --> 01:17:25.460
equals reproduction.

01:17:25.460 --> 01:17:27.890
So bonobos are
really interesting.

01:17:27.890 --> 01:17:30.030
What's the sex there about?

01:17:30.030 --> 01:17:31.880
One of the common themes
that comes through

01:17:31.880 --> 01:17:35.140
is it's about promoting
group cohesion,

01:17:35.140 --> 01:17:38.360
and one of the things that
people emphasize or focus on

01:17:38.360 --> 01:17:42.120
with bonobos is you look at all
sorts of other primate species,

01:17:42.120 --> 01:17:44.870
and what do they do when
they're upset about something?

01:17:44.870 --> 01:17:45.942
They groom each other.

01:17:45.942 --> 01:17:47.400
What do they do
when they're happy?

01:17:47.400 --> 01:17:48.090
They groom.

01:17:48.090 --> 01:17:49.860
What do they do--
social grooming,

01:17:49.860 --> 01:17:54.440
as termed the social glue, the
social lubricant of a society.

01:17:54.440 --> 01:17:56.210
You get a troop of
baboons that have just

01:17:56.210 --> 01:17:58.710
gotten a bad scare from
a lion, and as soon

01:17:58.710 --> 01:18:00.950
as the coast is clear,
everybody comes down

01:18:00.950 --> 01:18:03.500
and spends the next 30
minutes grooming each other.

01:18:03.500 --> 01:18:06.680
And sexual behavior
in bonobos appears

01:18:06.680 --> 01:18:09.020
to be serving a
very similar role--

01:18:09.020 --> 01:18:13.010
all about social cohesion
as well as decreasing

01:18:13.010 --> 01:18:15.470
individual tensions,
reconciliation,

01:18:15.470 --> 01:18:17.490
things of that sort.

01:18:17.490 --> 01:18:21.540
Now this flies on the face of a
dominant theory that was around

01:18:21.540 --> 01:18:23.570
in the last century,
the first part of it,

01:18:23.570 --> 01:18:26.040
and this was due to one
of the grand poobahs

01:18:26.040 --> 01:18:29.840
in this field, a guy, this
Brit named Solly Zuckerman.

01:18:29.840 --> 01:18:33.200
Solly Zuckerman, who eventually
became Sir Solly Zuckerman,

01:18:33.200 --> 01:18:35.290
which probably didn't
help him in society at all

01:18:35.290 --> 01:18:38.400
still despite that,
but old Zuckerman there

01:18:38.400 --> 01:18:42.110
was, for his time, the
embarrassed Wynne Edwards.

01:18:42.110 --> 01:18:43.860
He was the Lamarck
of the earliest

01:18:43.860 --> 01:18:45.290
part of the 20th century.

01:18:45.290 --> 01:18:47.240
The people who will
only be remembered

01:18:47.240 --> 01:18:49.850
for coming up with
Lamarckianism, old Lamarck

01:18:49.850 --> 01:18:52.710
or coming up with something
as idiotic as group selection.

01:18:52.710 --> 01:18:55.450
What Zuckerman came
up with was the notion

01:18:55.450 --> 01:19:00.690
that sexual behavior is purely
for promoting group cohesion

01:19:00.690 --> 01:19:02.890
and for decreasing violence.

01:19:02.890 --> 01:19:06.080
And all you need to do is go
to half the movies out there

01:19:06.080 --> 01:19:08.160
or study half the
species on Earth,

01:19:08.160 --> 01:19:11.890
and what you will see is
sexual behavior or inability of

01:19:11.890 --> 01:19:15.030
or unrequited or
whatever vanquished

01:19:15.030 --> 01:19:19.130
is the cause of the majority
of aggression in organisms

01:19:19.130 --> 01:19:22.670
out there in various
mammals, and that argues

01:19:22.670 --> 01:19:24.600
very strongly against it.

01:19:24.600 --> 01:19:28.020
So what you see in most species
that have been studied--

01:19:28.020 --> 01:19:31.280
it's a strong argument
against the Zuckerman stance.

01:19:31.280 --> 01:19:34.590
Nonetheless, you see in
some species like bonobos

01:19:34.590 --> 01:19:37.290
and Roughgarden's
argument, lots more species

01:19:37.290 --> 01:19:39.020
than people traditionally
would think,

01:19:39.020 --> 01:19:42.830
where instead you see sexual
behavior often serving

01:19:42.830 --> 01:19:47.800
a non-reproductive group
cohesion sort of role.

01:19:47.800 --> 01:19:51.620
What else does evolution have to
tell us about sexual behavior?

01:19:51.620 --> 01:19:53.930
One critical issue and
one that was touched

01:19:53.930 --> 01:19:56.510
on the first couple of
lectures is, what does it

01:19:56.510 --> 01:19:58.560
cost you to reproduce?

01:19:58.560 --> 01:20:02.740
And there we get the
hugely important asymmetry,

01:20:02.740 --> 01:20:06.620
which is sperm don't cost
a whole lot, whereas eggs

01:20:06.620 --> 01:20:10.620
and pregnancy and postnatal
care and all of that

01:20:10.620 --> 01:20:12.000
is hugely expensive.

01:20:12.000 --> 01:20:14.200
What is that the
driving force on

01:20:14.200 --> 01:20:16.770
according to all the
sociobiological thinking?

01:20:16.770 --> 01:20:19.420
The fact that in species
after species after species,

01:20:19.420 --> 01:20:22.000
females are more
selective about who

01:20:22.000 --> 01:20:24.700
they will mate with than
males, and it's usually

01:20:24.700 --> 01:20:27.870
the case the males are not
selective in the slightest.

01:20:27.870 --> 01:20:29.690
And what you've
got instead is just

01:20:29.690 --> 01:20:32.550
a couple of sperm that accost
you, and that's not a big deal.

01:20:32.550 --> 01:20:36.790
Increased female selectivity,
higher levels of it than males,

01:20:36.790 --> 01:20:39.840
argument being that it is
all about the differential

01:20:39.840 --> 01:20:42.410
costs of pregnancy.

01:20:42.410 --> 01:20:45.070
What we also saw was
not of pregnancy,

01:20:45.070 --> 01:20:47.540
but of reproduction
and raising of kids.

01:20:47.540 --> 01:20:49.420
What we saw was the
interesting realm

01:20:49.420 --> 01:20:51.500
where you got the
exception to that, which

01:20:51.500 --> 01:20:53.670
were the pair bonding species.

01:20:53.670 --> 01:20:56.560
The marmosets, for example,
and what we saw back

01:20:56.560 --> 01:21:00.910
when was the male does as
much child care as the female

01:21:00.910 --> 01:21:03.650
does, and the
females always twin.

01:21:03.650 --> 01:21:06.030
So around the time
that the kids are born,

01:21:06.030 --> 01:21:08.890
the female has put in far
more of the investment.

01:21:08.890 --> 01:21:10.790
She's gone through
the pregnancy in terms

01:21:10.790 --> 01:21:12.320
of caloric expenditure.

01:21:12.320 --> 01:21:15.770
The males do, if anything,
more of the child rearing

01:21:15.770 --> 01:21:18.090
in terms of carrying the
kid around when foraging,

01:21:18.090 --> 01:21:21.220
all sorts of costly stuff
like that, and eventually,

01:21:21.220 --> 01:21:27.630
what you see is the
curves don't do that.

01:21:27.630 --> 01:21:29.640
But at some point,
the cumulative amount

01:21:29.640 --> 01:21:31.830
of calories that the
male has expended

01:21:31.830 --> 01:21:33.450
is greater than the female.

01:21:33.450 --> 01:21:36.240
That's when you see
that cuckoldry business.

01:21:36.240 --> 01:21:38.510
That's where females
will potentially

01:21:38.510 --> 01:21:42.120
pick up and abandon, and because
the male has made the greater

01:21:42.120 --> 01:21:45.430
investment at that point, that
is seen very frequently in bird

01:21:45.430 --> 01:21:47.250
species with pair bonding.

01:21:47.250 --> 01:21:49.850
So we've got here an
exception to the argument

01:21:49.850 --> 01:21:53.230
that the cost of reproduction
and child raising

01:21:53.230 --> 01:21:55.490
is always greater for females
and, thus, will always

01:21:55.490 --> 01:21:58.530
produce greater female
pickiness for mates

01:21:58.530 --> 01:21:59.850
than you find in males.

01:21:59.850 --> 01:22:03.840
Nonetheless, you see
that an awful lot.

01:22:03.840 --> 01:22:05.170
What else do you see?

01:22:05.170 --> 01:22:07.590
A whole world not only
of female pickiness,

01:22:07.590 --> 01:22:10.000
but a whole world
of male attempts

01:22:10.000 --> 01:22:12.940
to control female
reproductive behavior.

01:22:12.940 --> 01:22:16.100
And this found in species
after species after species

01:22:16.100 --> 01:22:18.420
an obvious interpretation
there in terms

01:22:18.420 --> 01:22:21.370
of male-male
competition decreasing

01:22:21.370 --> 01:22:24.550
the ability of females to
mate with someone else.

01:22:24.550 --> 01:22:27.570
And that ranges
from primates who

01:22:27.570 --> 01:22:31.230
are in consortships, where
the male will do what is often

01:22:31.230 --> 01:22:33.910
termed mate guarding,
which is he tries

01:22:33.910 --> 01:22:36.390
to keep the female from
going near any other guy

01:22:36.390 --> 01:22:38.720
to all sorts of
other stuff as well.

01:22:38.720 --> 01:22:41.030
And you certainly see
this in the human realm.

01:22:41.030 --> 01:22:44.610
What are two cultural inventions
humans have come up with

01:22:44.610 --> 01:22:48.970
to decrease the likelihood--
by men-- to decrease

01:22:48.970 --> 01:22:51.580
the likelihood of women
being sexually active

01:22:51.580 --> 01:22:53.520
outside that relationship?

01:22:53.520 --> 01:22:55.770
The first one is
clitoridectomies,

01:22:55.770 --> 01:22:59.120
and something else that serves
a very similar function, which

01:22:59.120 --> 01:23:02.350
is inventions of things
like chastity belts.

01:23:02.350 --> 01:23:03.950
What's up with that?

01:23:03.950 --> 01:23:06.230
What you find are
cultural inventions

01:23:06.230 --> 01:23:10.490
like those in groups that tend
to have occupations where males

01:23:10.490 --> 01:23:12.560
disappear for long periods.

01:23:12.560 --> 01:23:14.980
For example, nomadic
pastoralists,

01:23:14.980 --> 01:23:16.800
where depending on
the time of year,

01:23:16.800 --> 01:23:19.800
you pick up with your camels
or your cows or whatever,

01:23:19.800 --> 01:23:22.150
and you, the guy, are going
to spend the next three

01:23:22.150 --> 01:23:24.930
weeks at the grazing area
that's a good five miles

01:23:24.930 --> 01:23:25.890
west of there.

01:23:25.890 --> 01:23:29.150
And what this is about--
the argument culturally

01:23:29.150 --> 01:23:32.640
for the clitoridectomies is
it decreases female pleasure,

01:23:32.640 --> 01:23:35.990
decreases the likelihood of
her having sex with someone

01:23:35.990 --> 01:23:37.430
else when you were elsewhere.

01:23:37.430 --> 01:23:39.940
What were chastity
belts about when

01:23:39.940 --> 01:23:43.100
the guy picked up and decided to
spend the next six years trying

01:23:43.100 --> 01:23:45.780
to liberate Jerusalem
from the Ottomans

01:23:45.780 --> 01:23:47.640
or whatever off in the Crusades?

01:23:47.640 --> 01:23:51.280
And just so you don't have any
ideas over the next half decade

01:23:51.280 --> 01:23:54.500
while I go die from the plague
somewhere in Eastern Europe,

01:23:54.500 --> 01:23:58.090
that's when those were,
again, a model of cultures

01:23:58.090 --> 01:24:00.040
where there were
extended periods

01:24:00.040 --> 01:24:02.950
of men being away from women.

01:24:02.950 --> 01:24:06.450
You have very often
elaborate cultural inventions

01:24:06.450 --> 01:24:10.030
for men trying to control the
reproductive access of women.

01:24:10.030 --> 01:24:13.030
What that also winds
up doing is explaining

01:24:13.030 --> 01:24:15.740
what was thought to
be the dominant models

01:24:15.740 --> 01:24:18.670
of reproductive success
and reproductive choice

01:24:18.670 --> 01:24:20.370
in all sorts of other species.

01:24:20.370 --> 01:24:22.190
And seen, for
example, in something

01:24:22.190 --> 01:24:26.080
like baboons, what you had
was termed the linear access

01:24:26.080 --> 01:24:27.990
model of reproduction.

01:24:27.990 --> 01:24:29.770
It goes as follows.

01:24:29.770 --> 01:24:31.850
You have a social
group-- for example,

01:24:31.850 --> 01:24:33.410
a baboon social
group-- and there

01:24:33.410 --> 01:24:37.440
is only one female who is in
estrus, only one female who

01:24:37.440 --> 01:24:38.440
is ovulating.

01:24:38.440 --> 01:24:40.210
Who winds up mating with her?

01:24:40.210 --> 01:24:42.580
The alpha male in the troop.

01:24:42.580 --> 01:24:45.920
Now instead, there's two
females who were ovulating.

01:24:45.920 --> 01:24:47.780
Who gets the two females?

01:24:47.780 --> 01:24:49.860
Numbers one and two
in the hierarchy.

01:24:49.860 --> 01:24:53.130
Three females-- numbers one,
two, and three get the female.

01:24:53.130 --> 01:24:56.810
And implicit in that is the
activeness implied in the word

01:24:56.810 --> 01:24:59.250
"get," the passive
lack of choice

01:24:59.250 --> 01:25:00.520
at the female end of things.

01:25:00.520 --> 01:25:03.680
This was the linear access
model in which male dominance

01:25:03.680 --> 01:25:07.780
rank was entirely predictive
of male reproductive success.

01:25:07.780 --> 01:25:10.460
So that's what people
thought lots about then.

01:25:10.460 --> 01:25:13.140
That was the original thinking
about the relationship

01:25:13.140 --> 01:25:16.000
between male dominance rank
and reproductive success.

01:25:16.000 --> 01:25:20.020
As we will see shortly,
it's not quite so clear.

01:25:20.020 --> 01:25:24.210
Lots of other species, where
you see males attempting

01:25:24.210 --> 01:25:26.130
in the evolutionary
sense, attempting

01:25:26.130 --> 01:25:28.840
to limit female access
to other males--

01:25:28.840 --> 01:25:32.210
this is the whole world
of copulatory plugs.

01:25:32.210 --> 01:25:36.940
Lots of dog canine related
species, where a semen plug is

01:25:36.940 --> 01:25:39.280
left there in the vagina
of the female, which

01:25:39.280 --> 01:25:43.720
soon hardens into a
plug like nothing else

01:25:43.720 --> 01:25:44.920
is happening there.

01:25:44.920 --> 01:25:46.220
You see that.

01:25:46.220 --> 01:25:47.610
There are other cases.

01:25:47.610 --> 01:25:51.780
There are fly species where
the males penis is barbed,

01:25:51.780 --> 01:25:59.261
and ooh, I heard a--
I'm not drawing that.

01:25:59.261 --> 01:26:01.370
What are you thinking?

01:26:01.370 --> 01:26:03.570
Where it's barbed and
where the barbs, in fact,

01:26:03.570 --> 01:26:07.820
go in the opposite direction,
point back at the male.

01:26:07.820 --> 01:26:11.930
Once you get the penis in there,
and it's not coming out again.

01:26:11.930 --> 01:26:15.200
It's like one of
those-- you put your--

01:26:15.200 --> 01:26:17.160
[LAUGHTER]

01:26:17.160 --> 01:26:19.390
Well, it's actually
not like one of those,

01:26:19.390 --> 01:26:20.710
but you get the point.

01:26:20.710 --> 01:26:22.110
And what's that about?

01:26:22.110 --> 01:26:24.800
The male leaves
his penis in there,

01:26:24.800 --> 01:26:27.220
which he manages to
do without afterward,

01:26:27.220 --> 01:26:29.050
because they can make new ones.

01:26:29.050 --> 01:26:31.590
And this is a very different
world you've got here.

01:26:31.590 --> 01:26:34.750
Then you've got the whole world
we've already heard about about

01:26:34.750 --> 01:26:39.490
sperm competition, of sperm from
one male in various fly species

01:26:39.490 --> 01:26:43.100
containing toxins that will
kill the sperm of another male.

01:26:43.100 --> 01:26:45.720
Then there's a whole
interesting world

01:26:45.720 --> 01:26:50.260
that goes on, which is when
males mate with a female,

01:26:50.260 --> 01:26:52.730
they do something
biochemically, which

01:26:52.730 --> 01:26:55.320
decreases the sexual
attractiveness

01:26:55.320 --> 01:26:57.470
of the female
subsequent to that.

01:26:57.470 --> 01:27:00.330
In a number of fly
species, males with mating

01:27:00.330 --> 01:27:03.920
release a chemical, which
decreases mating pheromone

01:27:03.920 --> 01:27:05.440
production in the female.

01:27:05.440 --> 01:27:08.650
And suddenly, nobody else
is interested in her,

01:27:08.650 --> 01:27:11.180
or there are other
flies species where

01:27:11.180 --> 01:27:14.950
males release a chemical, which
decreases sexual proceptivity

01:27:14.950 --> 01:27:15.980
in the female.

01:27:15.980 --> 01:27:19.550
Viciously clever ways
for males to control

01:27:19.550 --> 01:27:22.580
female reproductive
behavior after they've left.

01:27:22.580 --> 01:27:25.660
Male-male competitive
strategies.

01:27:25.660 --> 01:27:28.000
So what do you see at
the female end of things?

01:27:28.000 --> 01:27:31.380
No surprise, you see
female counterstrategies.

01:27:31.380 --> 01:27:34.450
One brilliant one
that evolved in humans

01:27:34.450 --> 01:27:39.480
is this relatively unique human
phenomenon of hidden ovulation.

01:27:39.480 --> 01:27:42.380
Yes, all that pheromone
stuff and smelling people's

01:27:42.380 --> 01:27:45.280
